================================================================================
  CIS UBUNTU 24.04 - MANUAL REMEDIATION GUIDE
  Based on Qualys Policy Compliance Scan Results
  Firewall: iptables only | OS: Ubuntu 24.04 LTS
================================================================================

CRITICAL WARNINGS BEFORE YOU BEGIN
------------------------------------
[!] Take a VM snapshot or backup before applying ANY changes.
[!] Keep a SECOND SSH session open while making SSH or firewall changes.
[!] Run 'sudo sshd -t' to validate SSH config before every restart.
[!] Test all changes in a NON-PRODUCTION environment first.
[!] Always allow port 22 BEFORE setting default DROP policy.


================================================================================
SECTION 1 - KERNEL MODULES (Disable Risky Filesystems)
================================================================================

Step 1: Open blacklist config
    sudo nano /etc/modprobe.d/cis-blacklist.conf

Step 2: Add the following lines to the file:
    install freevxfs /bin/true
    install hfs /bin/true
    install hfsplus /bin/true
    install jffs2 /bin/true
    install squashfs /bin/true
    install udf /bin/true
    install vfat /bin/true
    install cramfs /bin/true

Step 3: Unload modules immediately
    sudo modprobe -r freevxfs hfs hfsplus jffs2 squashfs udf vfat cramfs

Step 4: Verify (should return no output)
    lsmod | grep -E 'freevxfs|hfs|jffs2|squashfs|udf|vfat|cramfs'


================================================================================
SECTION 2 - APPARMOR (Mandatory Access Control)
================================================================================

Step 1: Install AppArmor and utilities
    sudo apt install apparmor apparmor-utils -y

Step 2: Enable AppArmor at boot
    sudo systemctl enable apparmor

Step 3: Start AppArmor service
    sudo systemctl start apparmor

Step 4: Set all profiles to enforce mode
    sudo aa-enforce /etc/apparmor.d/*

Step 5: Verify status
    sudo apparmor_status


================================================================================
SECTION 3 - FILESYSTEM (Sticky Bit & World-Writable Files)
================================================================================

Step 1: Set sticky bit on all world-writable directories
    df --local -P | awk '{if (NR!=1) print $6}' | \
    xargs -I '{}' find '{}' -xdev -type d -perm -0002 2>/dev/null | \
    xargs chmod a+t

Step 2: List world-writable files (review output carefully)
    find / -xdev -type f -perm -0002 2>/dev/null

Step 3: Remove world-write permission on each file found
    sudo chmod o-w <filename>

Step 4: Find unowned files
    sudo find / -xdev \( -nouser -o -nogroup \) 2>/dev/null

Step 5: Assign ownership to each unowned file found
    sudo chown root:root <filepath>


================================================================================
SECTION 4 - IPTABLES FIREWALL (IPv4 & IPv6)
================================================================================

[!] CRITICAL: Allow SSH (Step 9) BEFORE setting default DROP (Steps 10-11)
    or you will be permanently locked out of the server.

Step 1: Install iptables and persistence package
    sudo apt install iptables iptables-persistent -y

Step 2: Disable and stop nftables
    sudo systemctl disable nftables
    sudo systemctl stop nftables

Step 3: Flush all existing IPv4 rules
    sudo iptables -F
    sudo iptables -X
    sudo iptables -Z

Step 4: Flush all existing IPv6 rules
    sudo ip6tables -F
    sudo ip6tables -X
    sudo ip6tables -Z

Step 5: Allow IPv4 loopback
    sudo iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT
    sudo iptables -A OUTPUT -o lo -j ACCEPT

Step 6: Block non-loopback traffic from 127.x range
    sudo iptables -A INPUT ! -i lo -s 127.0.0.0/8 -j DROP

Step 7: Allow established/related IPv4 connections
    sudo iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT

Step 8: Allow DNS output
    sudo iptables -A OUTPUT -p udp --dport 53 -j ACCEPT
    sudo iptables -A OUTPUT -p tcp --dport 53 -j ACCEPT

Step 9: Allow SSH - DO THIS BEFORE SETTING DROP POLICY
    sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

Step 10: Set IPv4 default DROP policies
    sudo iptables -P INPUT DROP
    sudo iptables -P FORWARD DROP
    sudo iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT

Step 11: Allow IPv6 loopback
    sudo ip6tables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT
    sudo ip6tables -A OUTPUT -o lo -j ACCEPT
    sudo ip6tables -A INPUT ! -i lo -s ::1 -j DROP

Step 12: Allow IPv6 established connections
    sudo ip6tables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT

Step 13: Allow IPv6 SSH
    sudo ip6tables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

Step 14: Set IPv6 default DROP policies
    sudo ip6tables -P INPUT DROP
    sudo ip6tables -P FORWARD DROP
    sudo ip6tables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT

Step 15: Save rules to persist across reboots
    sudo netfilter-persistent save

Step 16: Verify rules
    sudo iptables -L -v -n
    sudo ip6tables -L -v -n


