SECTION 5 - SSH HARDENING
================================================================================

[!] Open a second SSH terminal before making changes.
[!] Always run 'sudo sshd -t' before restarting SSH.

Step 1: Create CIS SSH config drop-in file
    sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/99-cis.conf

Step 2: Add ALL of the following lines to the file:

    PermitRootLogin no
    MaxAuthTries 4
    MaxSessions 10
    IgnoreRhosts yes
    HostbasedAuthentication no
    PermitEmptyPasswords no
    PermitUserEnvironment no
    ClientAliveInterval 300
    ClientAliveCountMax 3
    LoginGraceTime 60
    X11Forwarding no
    AllowTcpForwarding no
    AllowAgentForwarding no
    Compression no
    LogLevel VERBOSE
    Banner /etc/issue.net
    Protocol 2
    StrictModes yes
    PrintLastLog yes
    TCPKeepAlive no
    GSSAPIAuthentication no
    KerberosAuthentication no
    DenyUsers root
    Ciphers aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes192-ctr,aes128-ctr
    MACs hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com
    KexAlgorithms curve25519-sha256,curve25519-sha256@libssh.org

Step 3: Validate SSH config (MUST show no errors before restart)
    sudo sshd -t

Step 4: Restart SSH only if Step 3 showed no errors
    sudo systemctl restart ssh

Step 5: Secure SSH config file permissions
    sudo chown root:root /etc/ssh/sshd_config
    sudo chmod 600 /etc/ssh/sshd_config

Step 6: Secure drop-in config file permissions
    sudo chown root:root /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/99-cis.conf
    sudo chmod 600 /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/99-cis.conf


================================================================================
SECTION 6 - LOGIN BANNER
================================================================================

Step 1: Edit the pre-login SSH banner
    sudo nano /etc/issue.net

Step 2: Add the following text:
    ***************************************************************************
    NOTICE: This system is for authorized use only.
    All activity is monitored and logged.
    Unauthorized access is prohibited and will be prosecuted.
    ***************************************************************************

Step 3: Copy banner to local console
    sudo cp /etc/issue.net /etc/issue

Step 4: Set correct permissions
    sudo chmod 644 /etc/issue.net
    sudo chmod 644 /etc/issue


================================================================================
SECTION 7 - PASSWORD QUALITY (pwquality)
================================================================================

Step 1: Install pam_pwquality module
    sudo apt install libpam-pwquality -y

Step 2: Open pwquality config file
    sudo nano /etc/security/pwquality.conf

Step 3: Add or update the following lines:
    minlen = 14
    dcredit = -1
    ucredit = -1
    ocredit = -1
    lcredit = -1
    maxrepeat = 3
    maxsequence = 3
    dictcheck = 1


================================================================================
SECTION 8 - PAM CONFIGURATION (Lockout & Password History)
================================================================================

Step 1: Backup common-auth before editing
    sudo cp /etc/pam.d/common-auth /etc/pam.d/common-auth.bak

Step 2: Open common-auth
    sudo nano /etc/pam.d/common-auth

Step 3: Add at the TOP of the file:
    auth required pam_faillock.so preauth silent deny=5 unlock_time=600

Step 4: Add at the BOTTOM of the file:
    auth required pam_faillock.so authfail deny=5 unlock_time=600

Step 5: Configure faillock settings
    sudo nano /etc/security/faillock.conf

Step 6: Add the following lines:
    deny = 5
    unlock_time = 600
    fail_interval = 900
    audit
    silent

Step 7: Backup common-password before editing
    sudo cp /etc/pam.d/common-password /etc/pam.d/common-password.bak

Step 8: Open common-password
    sudo nano /etc/pam.d/common-password

Step 9: Add at the TOP of the file:
    password requisite pam_pwquality.so retry=3

Step 10: Find the pam_unix.so line and add 'remember=5' at the end:
    Example: password [success=1 default=ignore] pam_unix.so obscure sha512 remember=5

Step 11: Remove nullok from all PAM files (prevents empty password login)
    grep -rl "nullok" /etc/pam.d/ | xargs sudo sed -i 's/nullok//g'


================================================================================
SECTION 9 - PASSWORD AGING & INACTIVE ACCOUNT LOCK
================================================================================

Step 1: Open login.defs
    sudo nano /etc/login.defs

Step 2: Set or update these values:
    PASS_MAX_DAYS   90
    PASS_MIN_DAYS   7
    PASS_WARN_AGE   14

Step 3: Lock accounts 30 days after password expires
    sudo useradd -D -f 30

Step 4: List all non-system users
    awk -F: '($3 >= 1000 && $1 != "nobody") {print $1}' /etc/passwd

Step 5: Apply aging to EACH user found in Step 4
    sudo chage --maxdays 90 --mindays 7 --warndays 14 <username>

Step 6: Verify aging settings per user
    sudo chage -l <username>


================================================================================
SECTION 10 - UMASK & SESSION TIMEOUT
================================================================================

Step 1: Set umask for root
    sudo nano /root/.bash_profile
    --> Add line: umask 027

Step 2: Set umask system-wide
    sudo nano /etc/profile
    --> Add line: umask 027

Step 3: Set umask in bash config
    sudo nano /etc/bash.bashrc
    --> Add line: umask 027

Step 4: Create session timeout script
    sudo nano /etc/profile.d/99-timeout.sh

Step 5: Add the following lines:
    TMOUT=900
    readonly TMOUT
    export TMOUT

Step 6: Set permissions on timeout script
    sudo chmod 644 /etc/profile.d/99-timeout.sh

Step 7: Verify timeout is set
    source /etc/profile.d/99-timeout.sh && echo $TMOUT
    --> Expected output: 900


================================================================================
SECTION 11 - CRON & AT HARDENING
================================================================================

Step 1: Remove deny files
    sudo rm -f /etc/cron.deny
    sudo rm -f /etc/at.deny

Step 2: Create allow files
    sudo touch /etc/cron.allow
    sudo touch /etc/at.allow

Step 3: Allow only root for cron and at
    echo "root" | sudo tee /etc/cron.allow
    echo "root" | sudo tee /etc/at.allow

Step 4: Set ownership and permissions
    sudo chown root:root /etc/cron.allow /etc/at.allow
    sudo chmod 600 /etc/cron.allow /etc/at.allow

Step 5: Secure crontab file
    sudo chown root:root /etc/crontab
    sudo chmod 600 /etc/crontab

Step 6: Secure cron directories
    sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.hourly
    sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.daily
    sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.weekly
    sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.monthly
    sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.d


================================================================================
SECTION 12 - FILE & DIRECTORY PERMISSIONS
================================================================================

Step 1: Secure /etc/passwd
    sudo chown root:root /etc/passwd
    sudo chmod 644 /etc/passwd

Step 2: Secure /etc/shadow
    sudo chown root:shadow /etc/shadow
    sudo chmod 640 /etc/shadow

Step 3: Secure /etc/group
    sudo chown root:root /etc/group
    sudo chmod 644 /etc/group

Step 4: Secure /etc/gshadow
    sudo chown root:shadow /etc/gshadow
    sudo chmod 640 /etc/gshadow

Step 5: Secure GRUB config
    sudo chown root:root /boot/grub/grub.cfg
    sudo chmod 400 /boot/grub/grub.cfg

Step 6: Set home directory permissions to 750
    awk -F: '($3 >= 1000 && $7 != "/usr/sbin/nologin") {print $6}' /etc/passwd | \
    xargs sudo chmod 750

Step 7: Find accounts without passwords
    sudo awk -F: '($2 == "" || $2 == "!") {print $1}' /etc/shadow

Step 8: Lock any account found without a password
    sudo passwd -l <username>


